	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>USDA assessment of the impact of quota abolition on the French dairy sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 October 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The USDA has published a report analysing the likely impact of the abolition of national milk production quotas on the French dairy sector, which is one of the largest dairy producers, processors and exporters in the EU. France accounts for 18% of EU milk deliveries, 23% of cheese production, 20% of butter production, 28% of skimmed milk power (SMP) production and 17% of whole milk powder production.</p><p>USDA notes that “dairy supply in the most productive regions of France has the potential to increase once quotas are abolished.” This would result in “higher exports of dairy commodities”. Indeed, “dried products production capacity is already being expanded”, meaning increased competition from French exporters on markets served by US dairy product exporters. Nigeria is a major ACP market where US and French companies compete for SMP sales. France currently accounts for 19% of EU SMP exports.</p><p>France has five prominent international dairy companies:</p>
<ul>

<li>Lactalis (with annual sales of €12.6 billion) </li>

<li>Danone (€11.2 billion)</li>

<li>Sodiaal (€4.4 billion)</li>

<li>Bongrain (€4.0 billion)</li>

<li>Bel (€2.5 billion). </li>

</ul>
<p>The report notes that there are also “15 smaller dairy processors with annual sales higher than 200 million euros each.” French dairy commodity production (of milk powder, whey and infant formula) is mainly targeted at export markets. According to the USDA analysis, the increase in milk production resulting from quota abolition is likely be used “to produce commodities for export, in response to growing global demand”. The expansion of “production capacity of dried dairy products, mainly milk powders, dried whey, and infant formula” is already under way, with “nine drying facilities being built or expanded” at a cost of €300 million.</p><p>In addition, China has emerged as a major market for French exports of infant formula (15% of total Chinese imports of infant formula).</p><p>In the short term, however, while French dairy producers generate high yields and are less dependent on purchased feed, they have been hit by rising feed costs in the past 12 months. High costs and low producer prices have “negatively impacted French milk production and dairy farmer income”. This has seen milk deliveries to French dairies fall by 2%</p><p>The USDA analysis notes that a report published by the National Research Institute in Agriculture (INRA) in 2010 suggested that milk production quota abolition “could result in wide fluctuation of European milk production, thereby contributing to increasing world price volatility” and greater disparity in the competitiveness of different EU milk production regions. It also maintained that quota abolition could lead to the emergence of nationally financed, region-specific policy measures to partially replace EU policy measures.</p><p>Against this background, USDA maintains that the French government had a strong influence on the framing of the EU Dairy Package, which included:</p>
<ol>

<li>“enhanced contractual relations between milk producers and dairy processors”;</li>

<li>“increased producers’ collective bargaining power through the creation of Producer Organizations (POs)”;</li>

<li>an expanded role for inter-branch [inter-professional] organizations to improve collaboration across the dairy sector.</li>

</ol>
<p>USDA indicates that France’s National Inter-Professional Centre for the Dairy Economy (CNIEL) is now “entitled to build milk price indicators and provide them as a reference to farmers and the industry”. The analysis notes that currently some 13% of total French milk deliveries are processed into high-end products, including 10% sold under designations protected under geographical indications (GIs) – 2% as organic milk, and 1% with a “mountain” designation. According to the analysis, EU milk quota abolition is likely to see increased French pressure to strengthen GI protection internationally, since GI-protected dairy products carry “major economic weight both in terms of sales and jobs”.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘France's dairy market situation - Perspectives on EU policy and on TTIP’, <i>GAIN Report</i> no. FR9145, 9 August 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/France's%20Dairy%20Market%20Situation%20and%20Perspectives%20on%20EU%20Policy%20_Paris_France_8-9-2013.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/France's%20Dairy%2...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>French companies are likely to be joining their Dutch and Danish counterparts in expanding milk production and exports in response to quota abolition, with West Africa once again appearing to be a target market (see <i>Agritrade</i> articles ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/End-of-dairy-quotas-leads-to-greater-external-focus-of-EU-dairy-companies" target="_blank">End of dairy quotas to lead to greater external focus of EU dairy companies</a>’, 4 March 2013 and ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Expanding-Dutch-corporate-involvement-in-local-milk-procurement-in-Nigeria" target="_blank">Expanding Dutch corporate involvement in local milk procurement in Nigeria</a>’, 15 April 2013).</p><p>Efforts are continuing across West Africa to develop smallholder commercial dairy production, but face serious challenges regarding efficiency and quality. This suggests that in the short term the development of commercial dairies linked to global supply chains may offer the most immediate prospects for meeting growing consumer demand. However, the success enjoyed in East Africa from promoting the commercial production of milk by smallholder farmers suggests that efforts to encourage expanded milk production should not be abandoned.</p><p>Concern over imports has led to calls from ROPPA, the West African regional farmers’ organisation, for increased tariff protection for milk products. This may end up primarily hurting consumers – but as regional demand for milk continues to rise, it is clear that the types of policy adopted in West Africa, linking milk powder imports to local dairy sector development, are likely to have an important bearing on the long-term impact of expanding EU milk powder exports to West African markets.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
